sect3.para:
Andreotti et al. ( 2020 ) have have noted that the C-SSRS C-SSRS and BSSI BSSI are often mentioned in the clinical research literature and both have sound psychometric support for their use. As probably the most widely used tool, the C-SSRS has multiple versions, including one designed for tracking between visits visits , one assessing lifetime suicidal thoughts suicidal thoughts and behavior in addition to recent symptoms, and a brief screener (Posner et al., 2011 ). The C-SSRS can either be a clinician- or self-administered measure. The clinician-administered version has the advantage of allowing for qualitative responses. The BSSI has the advantage of being quicker and easier to administer given that it relies on patient self-report and more objective, numerical responses. However, as noted, the C-SSRS is free and accessible (
https://​cssrs.​columbia.​edu/​
) whereas the BSSI is a proprietary measure that must be purchased, an option that may not be accessible to all clinicians or institutions. The BSSI is often used in clinical trials of patients who are suicidal as the “gold standard” tool for suicidal ideation.

sect2.para:
It is well understood that suicide risk assessments are anxiety-inducing for clinicians (Roush et al.,
            2018
         ; Wingate et al., 
            2004
         ). Therefore, during these encounters, it is important for clinicians to remain calm and adopt a balanced approach—avoiding over- or under-estimating a patient’s suicidality based on a single consideration. By its nature, a case formulation approach considers and integrates the full range of assessment data to conceptualize a patient’s relative risk and stability. Research has established that a clinician’s confidence in conducting suicide risk assessments is enhanced through access to trainings, even those that are brief (Wakai et al., 
            2020
         ). Given that a clinician’s comfort level is correlated to their consistent use of evidence-based practices (Roush et al., 
            2018
         ), training resources can offer vital guidance to performing effective assessments that can meaningfully enhance suicide prevention practices.

Many professional organizations offer their guidelines
            guidelines
          and general recommendations for accurately assessing suicidal risk in clinical populations, such as the American Psychological Association (APA; Knapp, 
            2020
         ) and the American Psychiatric Association (ApA; Jacobs et al., 
            2003
         ). As these resources highlight, there is no single instrument that is superior in screening for suicidal risk (Saab et al., 
            2022
         ), both in terms of sensitivity (i. e., reliably detecting truly at-risk individuals) and specificity (i. e., consistently identifying no-risk individuals). Instead, as Bernert and colleagues suggest, procedures must be standardized to ensure that the core competencies of suicide risk screening are being met across settings and professionals (Bernert et al.,
            2014
         ).

Until recently, standard practice has been in-person assessments. However, since the COVID-19 pandemic COVID-19 pandemic , telemedicine has skyrocketed and revolutionized the mental health field. While in-person assessments may be more suitable for patients with comorbid and complex conditions (e. g., substance use, violence; Shore & Lu, 2015 ), virtual platforms and telehealth-care provide undeniable conveniences such as timely assessment and safety planning, cost-effectiveness, increased continuity of care, and may be more considerate of patient preferences. It is recommended that while conducting virtual suicide risk assessments, clinicians should establish (1) the current location of the patient, (2) a plan for reconnecting if technology fails, (3) emergency contact information, (4) an assessment of their immediate lethal means access, and (5) a discussion of privacy requirements and confidentiality limits (for more information refer to:
https://​theactionallianc​e.​org/​resource/​covid-guidance-screening-suicide-risk-during-telehealth-visits
).
